1 (iii) one school–based administrator;
2 (iv) one public school teacher;
3 (v) one school counselor;
4 (vi) one parent of a student enrolled in a public school;
5 (vii) one pupil personnel worker;
6 (viii) one representative of a teacher’s union;
7 (ix) one representative of an institution of higher education;
8 (x) one representative of a nationally recognized educational
9 organization with expertise in student attendance or chronic absenteeism; and
10 (xi) any other individuals with expertise the State Superintendent
11 determines is relevant to the work of the Task Force.
12 (c) The Task Force shall elect a chair and vice chair from among its members.
13 (d) The State Department of Education shall provide staff for the Task Force.
14 (e) A member of the Task Force:
15 (1) may not receive compensation as a member of the Task Force; but
16 (2) is entitled to reimbursement for expenses under the Standard State
17 Travel Regulations, as provided in the State budget.
18 (f) The Task Force shall:
19 (1) collect and analyze data regarding chronic absenteeism by students
20 from schools in the State, including research, student attendance collection practices, and
21 trends in statewide and local student attendance;
22 (2) identify and evaluate local and national strategies and best practices to
23 address chronic absenteeism;
24 (3) identify differentiated and comprehensive responses for chronic
25 absenteeism that prioritize prevention and intervention;
26 (4) set a statewide goal for the reduction in chronic absenteeism
27 throughout the State;

