1 (5) develop and distribute guidance on identifying and preventing chronic
2 absenteeism to local school systems;
3 (6) develop and distribute a toolkit on identifying and preventing chronic
4 absenteeism for school leaders in each grade band (elementary, middle, and high school)
5 that includes culturally responsive and nonpunitive strategies for reducing student
6 absences; and
7 (7) make recommendations on:
8 (i) a single definition of chronic absenteeism;
9 (ii) the role that the community, public agencies, public school
10 systems and schools, parents, and students have in solving the problem of chronic
11 absenteeism;
12 (iii) the best practices for data collection relating to student chronic
13 absenteeism and tracking student attendance; and
14 (iv) the most effective practices to prevent and eliminate chronic
15 absenteeism that are culturally responsive and nonpunitive.
16 (g) On or before December 31, 2025, the Task Force shall report its findings and
17 recommendations to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State
18 Government Article, the General Assembly.
19 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
20 (a) On or before December 31, 2025, the State Department of Education shall
21 update regulations on student attendance to:
22 (1) incorporate the most effective practices identified by the Task Force to
23 Improve Attendance and Reduce Chronic Absenteeism in Schools established under Section
24 1 of this Act; and
25 (2) adopt regulations that include common definitions for chronic absence,
26 chronic absenteeism, and day of attendance.
27 (b) On or before June 30, 2026, the Department shall distribute the following
28 developed by the Task Force:
29 (1) the toolkit on identifying and preventing chronic absenteeism for school
30 leaders; and
31 (2) to each local school system in the State, guidance on identifying and
32 preventing chronic absenteeism that:

